http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/indieWIRE.description:
Sundance Institute will have the first-ever NEXT WEEKEND film festival, Aug. 8-11, 2013 at venues throughout Los Angeles. It will kick off with an outdoor screening of Chris Smith’s iconic cult documentary American Movie and Mark Borchardt’s horror film Coven Aug. 8 at Cinespia at the Hollywood Forever Cemetery. Chris Smith will introduce the films. Tickets ($12) are on sale now at www.ticketfly.com/purchase/event/312351. Sundance Institute Members will have priority admittance via a members-only line for this event at the Hollywood Forever Cemetery. This screening is co-presented with Acura. http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/indieWIRE.description:
Even as Toronto continued to add to its 2013 lineup and anticipation of the final season of "Breaking Bad" reached a fever pitch, the week seemed to belong largely to Paul Shrader and Bret Easton Ellis, whose controversial Hollywood-set drama "The Canyons" finally premiered after months of bad publicity and rumors about both its primary cast members and failure to show up on many spring festival lineups. This year's Toronto International Film Festival documentary world premieres include works by Penn & Teller, artist Chris Jordan, Jehane Noujaim and Leanne Pooley; and North American premieres by directors Errol Morris, Frederick Wiseman, Marcel Ophuls and Claude Lanzmann. (Full line-up is below.) Among the world premieres that programmer Thom Powers believes will pop for audiences is Chris Jordan's visually striking, almost wordless "Midway." http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/indieWIRE.title: TIFF 2013 Trailer Watch: 'Gravity,' '12 Years a Slave,' 'The Fifth Estate,' 'August: Osage County' and More UPDATED
http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/indieWIRE.description:
As TIFF 2013 approaches, running September 5 through 15, we're compiling an ongoing group of trailers for the buzzy titles set to screen at the fest. First up, Alfonso Cuaron's "Gravity," Steve McQueen's "12 Years a Slave," Bill Condon's "The Fifth Estate," John Wells' "August: Osage County," Justin Chadwick's "Mandela: Long Walk to Freedom," Ron Howard's "Rush," Denis Villeneuve's "Prisoners" and Keanu Reeves' "Man of Tai Chi." Watch below. Check out the first wave of titles announced by the Toronto International Film Festival, along with program notes on each film, here.
